{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566917"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:50:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:50:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18903"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18903"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.05,0.78,0.09,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11636"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80118"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11636"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18903"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65395"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"18"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"5678"},{"type":"tags","id":"11260"},{"type":"tags","id":"11349"},{"type":"tags","id":"11351"},{"type":"tags","id":"12867"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27373"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27374"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80118"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETwo medical students are discussing their clinical experiences while travelling home on a crowded train. One student begins describing an interesting case they saw that day, without mentioning the patient\u0027s name but including specific details about the condition, age, occupation, and unusual circumstances of presentation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes why this situation represents a breach of confidentiality?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sharing information without educational value","Failure to obtain written consent","Public discussion of identifiable patient information","Discussing clinical details outside hospital grounds","Sharing information with another healthcare student"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario demonstrates a breach of confidentiality through \u003Cstrong\u003Epublic discussion of identifiable patient information\u003C/strong\u003E. Even without using a name, providing specific details about age, occupation, and unusual circumstances could make the patient identifiable to others who might know them.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESharing information without educational value\u003C/strong\u003E - The educational value is not the primary concern; the issue is the public setting and identifiable information\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFailure to obtain written consent\u003C/strong\u003E - While consent is important for sharing patient information, the primary issue here is the public setting and potentially identifiable information\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiscussing clinical details outside hospital grounds\u003C/strong\u003E - The location itself is not the key issue; discussions can occur outside hospitals if in appropriate private settings\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESharing information with another healthcare student\u003C/strong\u003E - Sharing with other healthcare students is acceptable when done appropriately in private settings\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatient confidentiality must be maintained in all settings. Case discussions should occur in appropriate professional environments where privacy can be maintained. Even without names, combinations of specific details can make patients identifiable to others.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patient confidentiality is a fundamental ethical and legal obligation that requires healthcare information to be kept private unless there is explicit consent or legal requirement to disclose.","Breaches of confidentiality can occur through casual conversations, even when patient names are not mentioned.","Healthcare professionals must maintain confidentiality in all settings, including social situations and educational discussions."],"references":["Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 15]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx","Tariq RA, Hackert PB. Patient Confidentiality. 2023 Jan 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30137825. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30137825/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65395"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18903"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65395"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-17T13:14:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-17T13:14:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11636"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80118"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"typ